<DOC><DOCNO> AP881208-0184 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1825EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-France-Visas     12-08 0212</FIRST><SECOND>AM-France-Visas,0217</SECOND><HEAD>France Drops Visa Requirement For Seven Countries</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   France has decided to drop its visa requirement forvisitors from seven European countries that are not members of theEuropean Economic Community, the Foreign Ministry announced Thursday.   Government officials have said recently they may also rescind thevisa requirement for U.S. passport holders, but there has been noannouncement.   Citizens of Austria, Sweden, Norway, Finland, Iceland, Cyprus andMalta will again be welcome in France without visas, as they werebefore emergency measures put in place in September 1986 during awave of terrorist bombings in Paris.   ``This decision was taken in recognition of the reinforcement ofcooperation in Europe on security and the fight against terrorismand drug trafficking,'' said a Foreign Ministry spokesman.   France began demanding visas from people carrying passports ofall nations except the 11 other members of the EEC, plusSwitzerland. The decision was contested by officials from otherEuropean countries, especially Sweden and Austria.   Other countries affected by the 1986 decision include Algeria,Morocco, Tunisia and other African nations with traditionally closeties to France. French officials have said they wanted to avoid anyappearance of a racial criterion, with predominantly white countriesbeing the only ones exempt from the visa requirement.</TEXT></DOC>